\begin_layout Chapter
Free Carriers Optical Transitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cha:Free_Carriers_Optical_Transitions"

\end_inset

Absorption and emission of photons in semiconductors and semiconductor nanostruc
tures is the result of the complex interaction between light and condensed
 matter, i.e.
 photons, electrons, and ions.
 In order to capture the physics behind these processes, electromagnetism
 and quantum mechanics have to be combined, leading to a multitude of physical
 phenomena.
 This thesis focuses on the static properties of nanostructures, such as
 the constant emission or absorption of light.
 Therefore, the theory will be treated within the time-independent limit.
 The theory here is formulated within the classical limit of optical transitions
, where the quantum-mechanically treated carriers couple to a classical
 electromagnetic field.
 The resulting equations are famous and denoted as 
\emph on
semiconductor-Bloch equations
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haug2009"

\end_inset

.
 These equations have been used successfully over decades to describe optical
 properties within semiconductors.
 A fully consistent treatment of the light-emission would in principle require
 to work in a fully quantized picture (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kira1999"

\end_inset

), leading to the 
\emph on
semiconductor-luminescence equations
\emph default
.
 Such a treatment is beyond the scope of this thesis.
 The derivation presented here serves to illustrate the imposed approximations
 and to clearly document the implemented equations for nanostructures considered
 in this thesis using the electronic structure obtained using the methods
 outlined in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:Electronic_Properties_Semiconductors"

\end_inset

.
 This theory review is based mainly on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chuang1995,Jackson1998,Chow,Haug2009,Schafer2002"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chapter is organized as follows.
 We start by introducing the transformation of the crystal Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:crystal_H_final"

\end_inset

 into the second quantization.
 Then, the representation is rewritten in terms of the Bloch states, with
 a particular focus on the details arising when electronic states obtained
 using the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 envelope function method are used.
 In the present chapter, the Coulomb interaction will be excluded and thereby,
 only transitions between free carriers will be considered.
 Coulomb-correlated transitions will be treated in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:Coulomb_Correlated_Optical_Transitions"

\end_inset

.
 Then, we introduce the classical (monochromatic) light field and the self-consi
stent coupling to the electrons within the semiconductor nanostructure.
 The resulting equations allow the calculation the optical susceptibility
 and therefrom of the absorption, stimulated emission and refractive index
 change.
 In two final sections, we briefly explains how spontaneous emission can
 be obtained from optical susceptibility and cover the procedure to calculate
 required matrix elements from wavefunctions obtained using the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 envelope equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Second_Quantization_Formulation"

\end_inset

Second Quantization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electrons are fermions and consequently their wavefunction must be antisymme
tric to obey the Pauli exclusion principle.
 But instead of using a complicated expression for the antisymmetric wavefunctio
n, restricted to a constant number of particles, the Hamiltonian can be
 formulated in the second quantization that allows to include a varying
 number of particles and maintain the antisymmetry of the wavefunction naturally.
 Starting with the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:crystal_H_final"

\end_inset

 and separating the interaction with the external electromagnetic field
 leads to
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
H & = & \sum_{i}\underbrace{\left(\frac{\mathbf{p}_{i}^{2}}{2m_{0}}+U(\mathbf{r}_{i})\right)}_{H_{1}}+\underbrace{\sum_{i}\left(\frac{e}{m_{0}}\mathbf{A}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{p}_{i}+\frac{e^{2}}{2m_{0}}\mathbf{A}_{i}^{2}\right)}_{H_{e-EM}}\nonumber \\
 &  & +\underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j}\frac{e^{2}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}\left|\mathbf{r}_{i}-\mathbf{r}_{j}\right|}}_{H_{2}}.\label{eq:Separated_Hamiltonian-1}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Here the pure electro-magnetic Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{EM}$
\end_inset

 has been dropped as it constitutes within the present theory only an additional
 energy.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the eigenstates of the single particle Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H_{1}\varphi_{n}=E\varphi_{n}\end{equation}

\end_inset

with resulting energies and wavefunctions.
 Next, the vacuum ground state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and creation and annihilation operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{n}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{n}$
\end_inset

 are introduced.
 These operators create and destroy a particle with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}$
\end_inset

 and therefore act on the state
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{a}_{n}^{\dagger}\left|0\right\rangle =\left|1_{n}\right\rangle ,\,\,\hat{a}_{n}\left|1_{n}\right\rangle =\left|0\right\rangle ,\,\,\hat{a}_{n}\left|0\right\rangle =0,\,\,\hat{a}_{n}^{\dagger}\left|1_{n}\right\rangle =0.\label{eq:Creation_Annihilation_Operations}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The state span an Hilbert space of varying number of particles termed as
 the 
\emph on
Fock space.
 
\emph default
The Fock space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 can be defined in terms of the direct sum of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-particle Hilbert spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{N}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{F}=\mathcal{H}_{0}+\mathcal{H}_{1}+\mathcal{H}_{2}+\ldots\]

\end_inset

The antisymmetry of the state is preserved by the fermion commutation rule
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\hat{a}_{n}^{\dagger},\hat{a}_{n'}\right]_{+}=\hat{a}_{n}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{n'}+\hat{a}_{n'}\hat{a}_{n}^{\dagger}=\delta_{nn'}\label{eq:commutation_rel_1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\hat{a}_{n},\hat{a}_{n'}\right]_{+}=\left[\hat{a}_{n}^{\dagger},\hat{a}_{n'}^{\dagger}\right]_{+}=0.\label{eq:commutation_rel_2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

A valuable tool to transfer the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Separated_Hamiltonian-1"

\end_inset

 (or any other operator) into second quantization representation is given
 by the electron field operator
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\Phi}(\mathbf{r},t)=\sum_{n}\varphi_{n}(\mathbf{r})\hat{a}_{n}(t).\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, we switch from the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Schr
\backslash
"{o}dinger
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to the Heisenberg picture.
 For an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Schr
\backslash
"{o}dinger
\end_layout

\end_inset

 picture, the corresponding operator in the Heisenberg picture is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A_{H}=e^{iHt/\hbar}Ae^{-iHt/\hbar},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the Hamilton operator.
 As the Heisenberg picture will be generally used, the time-dependence of
 the operators is dropped from now on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Single Particle Hamiltonian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the field operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Phi}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

, the representation of the single-particle Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 in second quantization is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\hat{H}_{1} & = & \int d\mathbf{r}\hat{\Phi}^{\dagger}(\mathbf{r})H_{1}\hat{\Phi}(\mathbf{r})\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{j,k}\hat{a}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{k}\int d\mathbf{r}\varphi_{j}^{*}H_{1}\varphi_{k}\label{eq:Single_Particle_H_Second_Q}\\
 & = & \sum_{j}\hat{a}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{j}E_{j},\nonumber \end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

which is diagonal as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be an eigenfunction of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The representation in terms of second quantization could also be performed
 using another basis of the single-particle Hilbert space, but then 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Single_Particle_H_Second_Q"

\end_inset

 would not be diagonal in 
\begin_inset Formula $jk$
\end_inset

.
 Another detail is that here, the first quasi-particle, a particle occupying
 the eigenstates of the single particle Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

, has been introduced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Two Particle Hamiltonian: Coulomb Interaction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transformation of the two-particle interaction, the Coulomb term 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}$
\end_inset

, is similar, but more complicated.
 The result of the expansion is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{H}_{2}=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{j,k,l,m}\left\langle jk\mid v\mid lm\right\rangle \hat{a}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{k}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{l}\hat{a}_{m}.\label{eq:Two_Particle_Hamiltonian}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle jk\mid v\mid lm\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\langle jk\mid v\mid lm\right\rangle =\int d\mathbf{r}d\mathbf{r}'\varphi_{j}^{*}(\mathbf{r})\varphi_{k}^{*}(\mathbf{r}')\frac{e^{2}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}\left|\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}'\right|}\varphi_{m}(\mathbf{r})\varphi_{l}(\mathbf{r}').\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 are swapped in the integral compared to the annihilation and creation operators
 and that in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle jk\mid v\mid lm\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, the spin variable must be included, so
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\langle jk\mid v\mid lm\right\rangle \rightarrow\delta_{s_{j}s_{m}}\delta_{s_{k}s_{l}}\left\langle jk\mid v\mid lm\right\rangle .\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Particle_E_Interaction"

\end_inset

Particle – Electromagnetic Field Interaction Hamiltonian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next Hamiltonian to quantize is the electron–EM field interaction Hamiltonia
n 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{e−EM}$
\end_inset

 defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Separated_Hamiltonian-1"

\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{e−EM}$
\end_inset

 is a one-particle Hamiltonian and therefore its representation in the second
 quantization is obtained by applying the field operators as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Single_Particle_H_Second_Q"

\end_inset

, with the difference that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}$
\end_inset

 is diagonal in 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

but not in 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{e−EM}$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting expression reads
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{H}_{e-EM}=\sum_{j,k}\left(\frac{e}{m_{0}}\left\langle j\mid\mathbf{A}\cdot\mathbf{p}\mid k\right\rangle +\frac{e^{2}}{2m_{0}}\left\langle j\mid\mathbf{A}^{2}\mid k\right\rangle \right)\hat{a}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{k}.\label{eq:Particle_EM_Interaction_H}\end{equation}

\end_inset

To simplify the Hamiltonian and in order to get rid of the vector potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 in favor of the electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}=-\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 (Coulomb gauge assumed as before), the 
\emph on
dipole approximation
\emph default
 can be applied.
 As the crystal is a quasi-periodic structure, where the periodicity is
 much smaller than the photon wavelength of usual electromagnetic fields,
 the electric field can be assumed to be constant within the range of a
 lattice cell.
 This approximation removes the spatial dependence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 and reduces the second term 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle j\mid\mathbf{A}^{2}\mid k\right\rangle $
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\noun default
\color inherit
 to a contribution diagonal in 
\begin_inset Formula $j,k$
\end_inset

, and is therefore proportional to the number of electrons and does not
 contribute to any interband transitions.
 Therefore, it can be treated as an additional energy constant and thus
 be neglected.
 The remaining term, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{e}{m_{0}}\left\langle j\mid\mathbf{A}\cdot\mathbf{p}\mid k\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is more difficult to simplify and thus a simplified argument is brought
 here, while the full justification can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schafer2002"

\end_inset

.
 The first step is to relate the momentum matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 and the dipole transition matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

.
 The relation is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathbf{r},H_{1}\right]=\frac{i\hbar}{m_{0}}\mathbf{p},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the single particle Hamiltonian.
 Thus, the second term in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Particle_EM_Interaction_H"

\end_inset

 can transformed into
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\frac{e}{m_{0}}\left\langle j\mid\mathbf{A}\cdot\mathbf{p}\mid k\right\rangle  & = & \mathbf{A}\cdot\frac{e}{i\hbar}\left\langle j\mid\left[\mathbf{r},H_{1}(\mathbf{r})\right]\mid k\right\rangle \nonumber \\
 & = & \mathbf{A}\cdot\frac{e}{i\hbar}\left\langle j\mid\mathbf{r}H_{1}(\mathbf{r})-H_{1}(\mathbf{r})\mathbf{r}\mid k\right\rangle \\
 & = & \mathbf{A}\cdot\frac{e}{i\hbar}\left\langle j\mid\mathbf{r}\mid k\right\rangle \left(E_{k}-E_{j}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & -\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(E_{k}-E_{j}\right)\mathbf{A}\cdot\left\langle j\mid\mathbf{d}\mid k\right\rangle ,\nonumber \end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{d}=-e\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 is the dipole moment.
 The last step involved adding the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{d}_{j,k}\cdot\mathbf{E}-\mathbf{d}_{j,k}\cdot\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

, which with the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{e}{m_{0}}\left\langle j\mid\mathbf{A}\cdot\mathbf{p}\mid k\right\rangle =-\mathbf{d}_{j,k}\cdot\mathbf{E}-\left(\frac{\hbar}{i}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}+E_{j}-E_{k}\right)\mathbf{A}\cdot\mathbf{d}_{j,k}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is given by a plane wave 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}_{0}e^{i\left(\omega_{0}t-k_{0}r\right)}$
\end_inset

 with center frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 and the transition energies 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{k}-E_{j}$
\end_inset

 are ranged around 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, the expression in the brackets vanished and the sipole approximation for
 the Hamiltonian is obtained, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{H}_{e-EM}=-\sum_{j,k}\left\langle j\mid\mathbf{d}\cdot\mathbf{E}\mid k\right\rangle \hat{a}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{k}.\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final Hamiltonian for the crystal electrons 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Separated_Hamiltonian-1"

\end_inset

, can therefore be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{H}=\sum_{j,k}\left\langle j\mid H_{1}\mid k\right\rangle \hat{a}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{k}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{j,k,l,m}\left\langle jk\mid v\mid lm\right\rangle \hat{a}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{k}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{l}\hat{a}_{m}-\sum_{j,k}\left\langle j\mid\mathbf{d}\cdot\mathbf{E}\mid k\right\rangle \hat{a}_{j}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{k}.\label{eq:Crystal_Electron_H_General}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bloch States Formulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Up to now, we have ignored the specific form of the wavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Here we consider the wavefunction to be a Bloch function, as presented
 in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:Electronic_Properties_Semiconductors"

\end_inset

.
 Within a bulk crystal, the Bloch function is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\varphi_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r})=u_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r})e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 is lattice periodic and the exponential term is slowly varying.
 The current section aims now to transform 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Crystal_Electron_H_General"

\end_inset

 into Bloch states, which needs some clarifications and definitions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bloch-functions are required to be orthonormalized over the crystal
 domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_{\Omega}d\mathbf{r}\varphi_{n'\mathbf{k}'}^{*}\varphi_{n\mathbf{k}}=\delta_{n',n}\delta_{\mathbf{k}',\mathbf{k}}.\label{eq:Bloch_Orthonormality}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The goal now is to represent the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Crystal_Electron_H_General"

\end_inset

 using the field operator 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\Phi}(\mathbf{r},t)=\sum_{n,\mathbf{k}}\varphi_{n\mathbf{k}}\hat{a}_{n\mathbf{k}}(t)\end{equation}

\end_inset

in terms of the Bloch-functions.
 As the Bloch-states are not localized, the Fourier transform of certain
 quantities (such as the electromagnetic field or the Coulomb interaction)
 in the translational invariant directions will be used to simplify the
 Hamiltonian.
 For the spatial Fourier transform, the conventions are given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
w(\mathbf{r}) & = & \sum_{\mathbf{q}}w(\mathbf{q})e^{i\mathbf{q}\cdot\mathbf{r}},\label{eq:Fourier_Transform}\\
w(\mathbf{q}) & = & \frac{1}{\mathcal{A}}\int_{\mathcal{A}}d\mathbf{r}w(\mathbf{r})e^{-i\mathbf{q}\cdot\mathbf{r}}.\label{eq:Inverse_Fourier_Transform}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Normalization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of a quantum nanostructure, the Bloch function loses it’s plane
 wave dependence in the quantized direction and is therefore expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\varphi_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r},z)=\left|n\mathbf{k}\right\rangle =u_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r},z)e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}F_{n\mathbf{k}}(z).\label{eq:Bloch_WF_Nanostructure}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The free direction is represented by the plane-wave and the symmetry broken
 part by 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z)$
\end_inset

.
 The indices 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 now include the subbands.
 In the following, the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 will be used for the symmetry broken direction while 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 will denote the translational invariant direction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regarding the normalization, it is assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 is the volume of the translational invariant direction and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is the volume of the quantized direction.
 Obviously, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\mathcal{LA}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Bloch_Orthonormality"

\end_inset

 is still required to hold, but the normalization over the translational
 invariant direction is distributed into the lattice periodic part 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r},z)$
\end_inset

.
 The envelope function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z)$
\end_inset

 is then normalized over the quantized direction.
 Therefore, for a system quantized in 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 dimensions, the units of the wavefunction parts are given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\underbrace{\varphi_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r},z)}_{\frac{1}{\sqrt{m^{3}}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\Omega}}}=\underbrace{u_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r},z)}_{\frac{1}{\sqrt{m^{3-d}}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\mathcal{A}}}}e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}\underbrace{F_{n\mathbf{k}}(z)}_{\frac{1}{\sqrt{m^{d}}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\mathcal{L}}}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lattice-Cell Average
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A general problem of the approach using wavefunctions of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 envelope equation is that the lattice-periodic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r},z)$
\end_inset

 are not given in an explicit form.
 Only their symmetry properties, the fact that they are orthogonal to each
 other and some measurable quantities are available.
 Nevertheless, these properties are sufficient for building the Hamiltonian
 and calculating desired matrix elements, within the approximation that
 lattice-cell averaged quantities are used.
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 method, the envelopes and plane waves are assumed to vary little over a
 crystal cell.
 If an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 mainly acts on the lattice-periodic part, a matrix element between two
 wavefunctions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Bloch_WF_Nanostructure"

\end_inset

 can be simplified as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\langle n'\mathbf{k}'\mid A\mid n\mathbf{k}\right\rangle \approx\frac{\mathcal{A}}{V_{c}}\left\langle u_{n'\mathbf{k}'}\mid A\mid u_{n\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle _{V_{c}}\delta_{k',k}\int dzF_{n'\mathbf{k}'}^{*}(z)F_{n\mathbf{k}}(z).\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is replaced with it's lattice averaged quantity
\begin_inset Formula \[
V_{c}^{-1}\left\langle u_{n'\mathbf{k}'}\mid A\mid u_{n\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle _{V_{c}}.\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $V_{c}$
\end_inset

 denotes the crystal cell and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \right\rangle _{V_{c}}$
\end_inset

 the integration over it.
 The matrix elements found in the literature are related by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\mathcal{A}}{V_{c}}\left\langle u_{n'\mathbf{k}'}\mid A\mid u_{n\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle _{V_{c}}=\left\langle \tilde{u}_{n'\mathbf{k}'}\mid A\mid\tilde{u}_{n\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle \label{eq:Matrix_Elements_Relation}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the Bloch function normalized with respect to a single crystal cell.
 Therefore to determine values for the short-range operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle n'\mathbf{k}'\mid A\mid n\mathbf{k}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, only the envelope function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n\mathbf{k}}(z)$
\end_inset

 and the experimental value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \tilde{u}_{n'\mathbf{k}'}\mid A\mid\tilde{u}_{n\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 for the from bulk measurements are required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other case is given by the long-range operator 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, such as the Coulomb potential.
 In that case, the operator is constant over a lattice cell and the integral
 of the matrix element can be reduced using the orthogonality of the Bloch
 functions.
 The lattice-cell average reads
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle n'\mathbf{k}'\mid B\mid n\mathbf{k}\right\rangle  & = & \int_{\Omega}d\mathbf{r}dzu_{n'\mathbf{k}'}^{*}(\mathbf{r},z)e^{-i\mathbf{k}'\cdot\mathbf{r}}F_{n'\mathbf{k}'}^{*}(z)Bu_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r},z)e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}F_{n\mathbf{k}}(z)\nonumber \\
 & \approx & \int_{\Omega}d\mathbf{r}dz\frac{1}{V_{c}}\left\langle u_{n'\mathbf{k}'}\mid u_{n\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle _{V_{c}}e^{-i\mathbf{k}'\cdot\mathbf{r}}F_{n'\mathbf{k}'}^{*}Bu_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r},z)e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}F_{n\mathbf{k}}(z).\label{eq:Matrix_Element_Lattice_Cell_Average}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

A further simplification depends on the actual form of the considered operator.
 We return to this relation further in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Dipole-Matrix-Element"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Kinetic Term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To transform the kinetic part into the Bloch states, the eigenfunctions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n\mathbf{k}}(\mathbf{r},z)$
\end_inset

 of the single particle Hamiltonian are inserted into the field operator.
 Using that particular field operator, the kinetic term 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Crystal_Electron_H_General"

\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{H}_{1}=\sum_{n,\mathbf{k}}\hat{a}_{n\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{n\mathbf{k}}E_{n,\mathbf{k}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Interaction Term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remaining step is to quantize the electron - electromagnetic field interacti
on Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{e-EM}$
\end_inset

 within the dipole approximation.
 The Fourier representation of the electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r},t)$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r},t)=\sum_{\mathbf{q}}\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{q},t)e^{i\mathbf{q}\cdot\mathbf{r}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

As it is assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r},t)$
\end_inset

 is slowly-varying, the relevant contributions to the sum will be around
 very small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

.
 This allows to pull the 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\mathbf{q}\cdot\mathbf{r}}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\noun default
\color inherit
 factor out of the dipole integral in the calculation below.
 The resulting Hamiltonian then reads
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
 &  & \int_{\Omega}d\mathbf{r}dz\hat{\Phi}^{\dagger}H_{e-EM}\hat{\Phi}\\
 & = & -\sum_{n',\mathbf{k}',n,\mathbf{k}}\hat{a}_{n'\mathbf{k}'}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{n\mathbf{k}}\int_{\Omega}d\mathbf{r}dz\varphi_{n'\mathbf{k}'}^{*}\mathbf{d}\cdot\left(\sum_{\mathbf{q}}\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{q},t)e^{i\mathbf{q}\cdot\mathbf{r}}\right)\varphi_{n\mathbf{k}}\\
 & = & -\sum_{n',\mathbf{k}',n,\mathbf{k}}\sum_{\mathbf{q}}\delta_{\mathbf{k}'\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\mu}_{n'n,\mathbf{k}}\cdot\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r},t)e^{i\mathbf{q}\cdot\mathbf{r}},\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the dipole matrix element between two states 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n′$
\end_inset

 with same crystal momentum k is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\mu}_{n'n,\mathbf{k}}=\mathcal{A}\int_{\mathcal{L}}dzu_{n'\mathbf{k}}^{*}F_{n'\mathbf{k}}^{*}\mathbf{d}u_{n\mathbf{k}}F_{n\mathbf{k}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The delta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathbf{k}'\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 results from the plane wave and ensures momentum conservation.
 In other words, only direct transitions are allowed.
 Using the dipole matrix element, the Hamiltonian can finally be written
 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{H}_{e-EM}=\mathbf{-E}(\mathbf{r},t)\sum_{n',n,\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\mu}_{n',n,\mathbf{k}}\hat{a}_{n'\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{n\mathbf{k}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transformation of the two particle Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}$
\end_inset

 is presented in the next chapter.
 For the moment, it is assumed that the carriers are 
\emph on
uncorrelated
\emph default
 and their coulomb interaction is included in the single particle Hamiltonians.
 Collecting all single particle interactions, the Hamiltonian in the Bloch
 basis is given as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{H}=\sum_{n}E_{n}(\mathbf{k})\hat{a}_{n\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{n\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{-E}(\mathbf{r},t)\sum_{n',n,\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\mu}_{n',n,\mathbf{k}}\hat{a}_{n'\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{n\mathbf{k}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction of Holes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a semiconductor at 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0K$
\end_inset

, the valence band is fully occupied while the conduction band is empty.
 With increasing temperature, electrons in the valence band get excited
 into the conduction band and leave behind holes.
 Consequently, it is common to use for the valence band the absence of an
 electron, the hole, as a quasi particle.
 Therefore, if an electron with momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $−\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is created (
\begin_inset Formula $=\hat{a}_{-\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

), a hole with momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is annihilated (
\begin_inset Formula $=\hat{b}_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

) and vice versa.
 The sign is switched by convention.
 In order to introduce the concept of holes into the Hamiltonian, the commutator
 rules 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:commutation_rel_1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:commutation_rel_2"

\end_inset

 are used to reestablish the normal ordering of creation and annihilation
 operators.
 One obtains for the kinetic and dipole Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\hat{H} & = & \sum_{c,\mathbf{k}}E_{c}(\mathbf{k})\hat{a}_{c\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{c\mathbf{k}}-\sum_{v,\mathbf{k}}E_{v}(\mathbf{k})\hat{b}_{b\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{b}_{b\mathbf{k}}\nonumber \\
 &  & -\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r},t)\left(\sum_{c,v,\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\mu}_{cv,\mathbf{k}}\underbrace{\hat{a}_{c\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{b}_{v-\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}}_{\hat{p}_{vc,\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}}+\boldsymbol{\mu}_{cv,\mathbf{k}}^{*}\underbrace{\hat{b}_{v-\mathbf{k}}\hat{a}_{c\mathbf{k}}}_{\hat{p}_{vc,\mathbf{k}}}\right).\label{eq:Kinetic_Dipole_H}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Note that from now on, the summation is distinguished between summation
 over conduction bands indicated with 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and valence bands indicated using the index 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Kinetic_Dipole_H"

\end_inset

, transitions between conduction subbands and transitions between valence
 subbands have been neglected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One important point is that in the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Kinetic_Dipole_H"

\end_inset

, some terms can already be identified: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{c\mathbf{k}}=\hat{a}_{c\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{c\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 is the number operator counting the number of electrons in the band 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 with crystal momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{v\mathbf{k}}=\hat{b}_{b-\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{b}_{b-\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 is the number operator counting the holes in the valence band 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{vc,\mathbf{k}}=\hat{b}_{v-\mathbf{k}}\hat{a}_{c\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 is named 
\emph on
microscopic polarization
\emph default
 and is given by the off-diagonal density matrix element, giving the correlation
 between a particle in one band and an empty state in the other.
 In a simplistic view, the dipole matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}_{cv,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 gives the coupling strength of such a correlation to an electric field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Carrier_Statistics"

\end_inset

Carrier Statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main interest of the current work is the continuous emission of light
 of a semiconductor, which is given in the steady state of the system.
 In the limit of small light intensity and therefore absence of spectral-hole
 burning, it can be assumed that the carriers relax into their quasi-equilibrium
 distributions, given by the Fermi distributions for the electrons in the
 conduction band
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
n_{c\mathbf{k}}=\left\langle \hat{n}_{c\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle =f_{c\mathbf{k}}=\frac{1}{1+e^{\left(E_{c}(\mathbf{k})-E_{F,c}\right)/k_{B}T}}\label{eq:Conduction_Band_Electrons_Fermi}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the holes in the valence band
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
n_{v\mathbf{k}}=\left\langle \hat{n}_{v\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle =f_{v\mathbf{k}}=\frac{1}{1+e^{\left(E_{F,v}-E_{v}(\mathbf{k})\right)/k_{B}T}}.\label{eq:Valence_Band_Hole_Fermi}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{F,c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{F,v}$
\end_inset

 denote the quasi-Fermi levels of the electrons and holes, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}$
\end_inset

 is Boltzmann’s constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 denotes the temperature.
 The Fermi levels can be calculated from the 3D carrier density 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
N=\frac{1}{\Omega}\sum_{c\mathbf{k}}f_{c\mathbf{k}}\label{eq:Electron_3D_Density}\end{equation}

\end_inset

for electrons and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P=\frac{1}{\Omega}\sum_{v\mathbf{k}}f_{v\mathbf{k}}\label{eq:Holes_3D_Density}\end{equation}

\end_inset

for holes.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 denotes the volume of the system, which is usually unknown.
 When the sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is transformed into an integral
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{\mathbf{k}}\rightarrow\frac{2\mathcal{A}}{(2\pi)^{d}}\int d\mathbf{k}\end{equation}

\end_inset

the unknown 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 volume is removed and one ends up with known quantities (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}=\Omega/\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 denotes the dimensionality of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

-space.
 Note the factor 2 which stems from the implicit summation over the spin
 states.
 For an ideal 2D quantum well, the electrons are free to move only in the
 plane of the active layer, so that the summation over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 is restricted to two dimensions according to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{\mathbf{k}}\rightarrow\frac{2\mathcal{A}}{(2\pi)^{2}}\int dk2\pi k,\label{eq:2D_Symmetric_k_Sum_Integral}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we assume that the function summed over is cylindrically symmetric
 (which is a reasonable assumption for the subband structure near the zone
 center 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}=0$
\end_inset

).
 As the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 dependence of the distributions for general band structures is quite evolved,
 an analytical inversion of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Electron_3D_Density"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Holes_3D_Density"

\end_inset

 is not feasible.
 Therefore, the simplest way to calculate the quasi-Fermi levels is to perform
 a numerical Newton procedure to find the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{0}−N(E_{F})=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Transitions Calculation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Classically, an electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

 in a semiconductor induces dipoles.
 These dipoles create a macroscopic polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

.
 The induced polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}(t)$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 depends on the electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}(t')$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t'<t$
\end_inset

.
 Their relation is defined in terms of a time-dependent susceptibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(t-t')$
\end_inset

 (in this case a scalar)
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{P}(t)=\epsilon_{b}\int_{\infty}^{t}\chi(t-t')\mathbf{E}(t')dt'.\label{eq:Polarization_Time_Domain}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Taking the Fourier transform of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Polarization_Time_Domain"

\end_inset

 leads to the more convenient form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{P}(\omega)=\epsilon_{b}\chi(\omega)\mathbf{E}(\omega).\label{eq:Polarization_Freq_Domain}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The polarization influences the electric field via the electric displacement
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{D}=\epsilon\mathbf{E}=\epsilon_{b}\mathbf{E}+\mathbf{P}.\label{eq:Electric_Displacement}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore, the creation of dipoles and the amplification of an electric
 field needs to be treated self-consistently.
 The aim is therefore to calculate the polarization quantum-mechanically
 in the presence of an electric field and obtain a self-consistent formula
 for the steady state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a first step, Maxwell’s equations are rewritten to give a single relation
 between the electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

 and the macroscopic polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

.
 Taking the curl of
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla\times\mathbf{H}-\frac{\partial\mathbf{D}}{\partial t}=\mathbf{j}\label{eq:Maxwells_1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and using 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla\times\mathbf{E}=-\frac{\partial\mathbf{B}}{\partial t},\label{eq:Maxwells_2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

ones obtains
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\nabla\times\nabla\times\mathbf{E} & = & -\nabla\times\frac{\partial\mu_{0}\mathbf{H}}{\partial t},\\
\nabla\left(\nabla\cdot\mathbf{E}\right)-\nabla^{2}\mathbf{E} & = & -\mu_{0}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(\nabla\times\mathbf{H}\right).\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

On the left hand side, the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\mathbf{E}=0$
\end_inset

 vanishes, assuming charge neutrality and homogeneous media.
 On the right hand side, using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Maxwells_1"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 is replaced by the electric displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla\left(\nabla\cdot\mathbf{E}\right)-\nabla^{2}\mathbf{E}\approx-\nabla^{2}\mathbf{E}=-\mu_{0}\frac{\partial^{2}\mathbf{D}}{\partial t^{2}},\end{equation}

\end_inset

which now allows to introduce the macroscopic polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Electric_Displacement"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
-\nabla^{2}\mathbf{E}+\mu_{0}\epsilon_{b}\frac{\partial^{2}\mathbf{E}}{\partial t^{2}}=-\mu_{0}\frac{\partial^{2}\mathbf{P}}{\partial t^{2}}.\label{eq:Helmholtz_Eq}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This equation is the
\emph on
 inhomogeneous Helmholtz equation
\emph default
.
 The next step is to assume a monochromatic electrical field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

 (traveling into 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-direction) given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{E}(z,t)=\frac{1}{2}\hat{e}_{i}E(z)e^{i\left(k_{0}z-\nu t-\phi(z)\right)}+\mbox{c.c},\label{eq:Electrical_Field_Ansatz}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{0}=\nu n/c$
\end_inset

 is the photo wavenumber and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a unit vector orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{e}_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(z)$
\end_inset

 us the real phase shift and 
\begin_inset Formula $E(z)$
\end_inset

 is the real field amplitude, varying little within an optical wavelength.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 denotes the field frequency.
 It is assumed that the spacial strong oscillatory part is properly described
 by the plane wave.
 The electric field induces a polarization 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{P}(z,t)=\frac{1}{2}\hat{e}_{i}P(z)e^{i\left(k_{0}z-\nu t-\phi(z)\right)}+\mbox{c.c}.\label{eq:Polarization_Ansatz}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The next step is to insert 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Electrical_Field_Ansatz"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Polarization_Ansatz"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Helmholtz_Eq"

\end_inset

 and neglect all terms containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}^{2}E(z)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}^{2}\phi(z)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}E(z)\partial_{z}\phi(z)$
\end_inset

.
 This approach is denoted as the 
\emph on
slowly varying envelope approximation
\emph default
 and one ends up with an equation for the amplitudes 
\begin_inset Formula $E(z)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P(z)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\partial_{z}E(z)-iE(z)\partial_{z}\phi(z)=i\frac{\mu_{0}\nu^{2}}{2k_{0}}\chi(z)E(z).\end{equation}

\end_inset

Splitting into real and imaginary parts and using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Polarization_Freq_Domain"

\end_inset

, the self consistent equations are obtained as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\partial_{z}E(z) & = & -\frac{\nu}{2\epsilon_{0}nc}\Im\left\{ P(z)\right\} =-\frac{k_{0}}{2}\chi^{\prime\prime}(z)E(z),\label{eq:Slow_Varying_Envelope_Imag}\\
\partial_{z}\phi(z) & = & -\frac{1}{E(z)}\frac{\nu}{2\epsilon_{0}nc}\Re\left\{ P(z)\right\} =-\frac{k_{0}}{2}\chi^{\prime}(z),\label{eq:Slow_Varying_Envelope_Real}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=\chi^{\prime}+i\chi^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

 is the electrical susceptibility of the system.
 Consequently, the intensity gain (amplitude is half of it) is defined by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G=-k_{0}\chi^{\prime\prime},\label{eq:Intensity_Gain}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the change of refractive index (via a continuous phase change) is given
 by the real part of the susceptibility
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\delta n}{n}=\frac{\chi^{\prime}}{2}.\label{eq:Refractive_Index_Change}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The absorption can be obtained from the intensity gain through 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=-G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quantum Microscopic Polarization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second step is to couple quantum mechanical observables to the solids
 properties.
 The dipole interaction between electrons and the electric field is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H_{e-EM}=-V\mathbf{P}\cdot\mathbf{E},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the volume of the system and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the macroscopic polarization density
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{P}=\frac{1}{V}\sum_{n,n',\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\mu}_{n'n,\mathbf{k}}\left\langle \hat{a}_{n'\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{n\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle =\frac{1}{V}\sum_{c.v.\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\mu}_{cv,\mathbf{k}}p_{vc,\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}+\boldsymbol{\mu}_{cv,\mathbf{k}}^{*}p_{vc,\mathbf{k}}\end{equation}

\end_inset

from which the optical properties 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Intensity_Gain"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Refractive_Index_Change"

\end_inset

 can be obtained.
 Here, the expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{vc,\mathbf{k}}=\left\langle \hat{p}_{vc,\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 has been used.
 The amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $P(z)$
\end_inset

 of the macroscopic polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}(z,t)$
\end_inset

 used for the optical properties is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P(z)=2e^{-i\left(k_{0}z-\nu t-\phi(z)\right)}\frac{1}{V}\sum_{c.v.\mathbf{k}}\boldsymbol{\mu}_{cv,\mathbf{k}}^{*}p_{vc,\mathbf{k}}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The other term of the polarization containing 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $p_{vc,\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\noun default
\color inherit
 is related to the complex conjugate part of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Polarization_Ansatz"

\end_inset

 and is not required to determine the macroscopic amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $P(z)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Heisenberg's Equation of Motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to calculate the expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

, the equation of motion of the microscopic polarization operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

  has to be solved.
 Here the index 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is used for the conduction band and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 for the valence band of interest.
 The indices 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 will be used for the summation over remaining conduction and valence bands.
 The Heisenberg equation of motion for a time dependent operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chow"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{O}=\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[\hat{H},\hat{O}\right].\label{eq:Heisenberg_Eq_Motion}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Applying to the microscopic polarization operator, one obtains
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}=\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[\hat{H}_{1},\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\right]+\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[\hat{H}_{e-EM},\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\right].\end{equation}

\end_inset

The evaluation of the first commutator gives
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(E_{c}(\mathbf{k})-E_{v}(\mathbf{k})\right)\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

For the second operator
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{1}{V}\sum_{c,v,\mathbf{k}'}\boldsymbol{\mu}_{cv,\mathbf{k}'}\hat{p}_{vc,\mathbf{k}'}^{\dagger}+\boldsymbol{\mu}_{cv,\mathbf{k}'}^{*}\hat{p}_{vc,\mathbf{k}'},\end{equation}

\end_inset

the second term containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{vc,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 vanishes because four anticommuting exchanges are required (leading to
 no sign change) to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\hat{H}-\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\hat{H}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, one is left with the first term, where operators are exchanged
 to transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}\hat{p}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}\hat{H}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\hat{a}_{c\mathbf{k}'}^{\dagger}\hat{b}_{c\mathbf{-k}'}^{\dagger}\hat{b}_{n\mathbf{k}}\hat{a}_{m\mathbf{k}} & \rightarrow & \hat{a}_{c\mathbf{k}'}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{m\mathbf{k}}\delta_{v,n}\delta_{\mathbf{k}',\mathbf{k}}\nonumber \\
 &  & +\hat{b}_{v-\mathbf{k}'}^{\dagger}\hat{b}_{n\mathbf{-k}}\delta_{c,m}\delta_{\mathbf{k}',\mathbf{k}}\\
 &  & -\delta_{\mathbf{k}',\mathbf{k}}\delta_{n,v}\delta_{m,c}+\hat{p}\hat{H}.\nonumber \end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The delta functions of the remaining terms lead in the sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $c,v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}'$
\end_inset

 to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{c}\hat{a}_{c\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{m\mathbf{k}}+\sum_{v}\hat{b}_{v-\mathbf{k}}\hat{b}_{n-\mathbf{k}}-1.\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, the sums over 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 except for
\begin_inset Formula $c=m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=n$
\end_inset

 will vanish when later the expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{a}_{c\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{m\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is taken.
 Therefore, the sums are neglected from now on.
 This approximation scheme is called the 
\emph on
random phase approximation
\emph default
.
 The hand waving argument is that the expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{a}_{n'\mathbf{k}'}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{n\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 has a dominant time-dependence
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\langle \hat{a}_{n'\mathbf{k}'}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{n\mathbf{k}}\right\rangle \propto e^{i\left(\omega_{n'\mathbf{k}'}-\omega_{n\mathbf{k}}\right)t}\label{eq:Random_Phase_Apprx}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and therefore rapidly oscillates for 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{n'\mathbf{k}'}\neq\omega_{n\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\noun default
\color inherit
 and then averages out over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The terms with 
\begin_inset Formula $c=m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=n$
\end_inset

 are the density operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{m\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{n\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 Collecting everything and taking the expectation values, the equation of
 motion of the free carrier microscopic polarization is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}} & = & -\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(E_{m}(\mathbf{k})-E_{n}(\mathbf{k})\right)\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\nonumber \\
 &  & -\frac{i}{\hbar}\mathbf{E}(z,t)\cdot\boldsymbol{\mu}_{mn,\mathbf{k}}\left(\hat{n}_{m\mathbf{k}}+\hat{n}_{n\mathbf{k}}-1\right)\nonumber \\
 &  & +\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\right|_{col.}.\label{eq:SC_Bloch_Eq_1}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Similar equations can be formulated for the carriers density operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{m\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}_{n\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\frac{d\hat{n}_{n\mathbf{k}}}{dt} & = & -\frac{2}{\hbar}\Im\left\{ \mathbf{E}(z,t)\cdot\boldsymbol{\mu}_{\mathbf{k}}\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}^{*}\right\} \nonumber \\
 &  & +\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\hat{n}_{n,\mathbf{k}}\right|_{col.},\label{eq:SC_Bloch_Eq_2}\\
\frac{d\hat{n}_{m\mathbf{k}}}{dt} & = & -\frac{2}{\hbar}\Im\left\{ \mathbf{E}(z,t)\cdot\boldsymbol{\mu}_{\mathbf{k}}\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}^{*}\right\} \nonumber \\
 &  & +\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\hat{n}_{m,\mathbf{k}}\right|_{col.}.\label{eq:SC_Bloch_Eq_3}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

These equations constitute the
\emph on
 semiconductor Bloch equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haug2009"

\end_inset

,
\emph default
 for the free-carrier case.
 These semiconductor Bloch equations contain the basis for most of our understan
ding of the optical properties of semiconductors and semiconductor microstructur
es.
 Depending on the strength and time dynamics of the field, one can distinguish
 several relevant regimes: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the low excitation regime in which the exciton resonances - sometimes accompanie
d by exciton molecule (biexciton) resonances - dominate the optical properties.
 The interaction with phonons provides the most important relaxation and
 dephasing mechanism.
 As the density increases gradually, scattering between electron-hole excitation
s also becomes important.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the high excitation regime in which an electron-hole plasma is excited.
 Here, the screening of the Coulomb interaction by the optically excited
 carriers and the collective plasma oscillations are the relevant physical
 phenomena.
 The main dissipative mechanism is the carrier-carrier Coulomb scattering.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the quasi-equilibrium regime which can be realized on relatively long time
 scales.
 Here, the excitations have relaxed into a quasi-equilibrium and can be
 described by thermal distributions.
 The relatively slow approach to equilibrium can be described by a semi-classica
l relaxation and dephasing kinetics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the ultrafast regime in which quantum coherence and the beginning dissipation
 determine the optical response.
 The process of decoherence, of the beginning relaxation and the build-up
 of correlations, e.g., by a time-dependent screening are governed by the
 quantum kinetics with memory structure of the carrier-carrier and carrier-phono
n scattering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thoughout this thesis, the high-excitation and quasi-equilibrium regimes
 dominate the theoretical analysis of the discussed quantum structures.
 Generally, the scattering terms in the semiconductor Bloch equations describe
 all the couplings of the polarizations and populations, i.e., of the single-parti
cle density matrix elements to higher-order correlations, such as two-particle
 and phonon- or photon-assisted density matrices.
 However, in many cases one can identify specific physical mechanisms that
 dominate the scattering terms in some of the excitation regimes listed
 above.
 For example, in the low excitation regime often the coupling of the excited
 carriers to phonons determines relaxation and dephasing, whereas at high
 carrier densities carrier-carrier scattering dominates.
 For relatively long pulses, Markov approximations for the scattering processes
 are often justified, and the scattering terms can be described by Boltzmann-lik
e scattering rates due to carrier-phonon or carrier-carrier scattering,
 respectively 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haug2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all situations, the semiconductor Bloch equations are a very suitable
 theoretical framework which, however, has to be supplemented with an appropriat
e treatment of the scattering terms in order to describe the various aspects
 of the rich physics which one encounters in pulse excited semiconductors.
 In general, the semiconductor Bloch equations have to be treated together
 with the Maxwell equations for the light field in order to determine the
 optical response.
 This self consistent coupling of Maxwell and semiconductor Bloch equations
 (for shortness also called Maxwell-semiconductor-Bloch equations) is needed
 as soon as spatially extended structures are analyzed where light propagation
 effects become important.
 Relevant examples are the polariton effects, as well as semiconductor lasers
 or the phenomenon of optical bistability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haug2009"

\end_inset

.
 In optically thin samples, however, where propagation effects are unimportant,
 the transmitted light field is proportional to the calculated polarization
 field.
 Under these conditions one can treat the semiconductor Bloch equations
 separately from Maxwell's equations to calculate the optical response.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first term in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SC_Bloch_Eq_2"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SC_Bloch_Eq_3"

\end_inset

 describes the generation of electrons and holes pairs by the absorption
 of light.
 As long as the scattering terms are ignored, the rate of change of the
 hole population 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SC_Bloch_Eq_3"

\end_inset

 is identical to the rate of change of the electron population 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SC_Bloch_Eq_2"

\end_inset

.
 The scattering terms require a more sophisticated treatment and some of
 these will be addressed in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:Coulomb_Correlated_Optical_Transitions"

\end_inset

.
 For the moment, scattering is approximated using a a simple phenomenological
 decay rate model given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\right|_{col.} & \approx & -\gamma\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}},\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Solving the Equation for Free Carriers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SC_Bloch_Eq_1"

\end_inset

 one could use the approach given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chow"

\end_inset

 and formally integrate the differential equation.
 A simpler way is to replace the oscillating microscopic polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 by its slowly varying envelope
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
s_{nm,\mathbf{k}}=p_{nm,\mathbf{k}}e^{-i\left(k_{0}z-\nu t-\phi(z)\right)},\label{eq:Slowly_Varying_Envelope_Polarization}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is the frequency of the optical field, and solve for the steady state of
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}s_{nm,\mathbf{k}}=0.\end{equation}

\end_inset

Inserting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Slowly_Varying_Envelope_Polarization"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Electrical_Field_Ansatz"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SC_Bloch_Eq_1"

\end_inset

, and skipping all fast oscillating parts (as they should average out over
 time), leads to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
p_{nm,\mathbf{k}}=-\frac{i}{\hbar}\frac{E(z)}{2}\mu_{mn,\mathbf{k}}\frac{n_{m\mathbf{k}}+n_{n\mathbf{k}}-1}{i\left(\omega_{n,m}(\mathbf{k})-\nu\right)+\gamma}e^{-i\left(k_{0}z-\nu t-\phi(z)\right)},\label{eq:FCT_Micro_Polarization}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{n,m}(\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hbar\omega_{n,m}(\mathbf{k})=E_{m}(\mathbf{k})-E_{n}(\mathbf{k}).\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Inserting this equation into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Intensity_Gain"

\end_inset

 we obtain the expression for the absorption spectrum 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\alpha_{FCT}(\nu)=k_{0}\chi^{\prime\prime}=-\frac{\nu}{\epsilon_{0}n_{b}c}\frac{1}{\hbar}\frac{1}{\Omega}\sum_{n,m,\mathbf{k}}\left|\mu_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\right|^{2}\left(n_{nk}+n_{m\mathbf{k}}-1\right)\frac{\gamma}{\left(\omega_{n,m}(\mathbf{k})-\nu\right)^{2}+\gamma^{2}}.\label{eq:Absorption_FCT}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, the
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 denotes the dipole matrix element, between the subbands 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, along the polarization of the light field, resulting from the scalar product
 between the monochromatic light field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

 and the dipole 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to evaluate numerically the absorption spectrum we make the following
 assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The system under discussion is 2 dimensional and all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

-vector dependencies are cylindrically symmetric.
 Thus, we can use 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2D_Symmetric_k_Sum_Integral"

\end_inset

 transformation from summation to integration for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

-vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The system undergoes a rapid equilibration of electrons and holes into Fermi-Dir
ac distributions, which, assuming that the conduction band and the valence
 band are two carrier reservoirs, leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{e\mathbf{k}}=f_{e\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{h\mathbf{k}}=f_{h\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under these assumptions, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Absorption_FCT"

\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\alpha_{FCT}(\nu)=-\frac{\nu}{\hbar c\epsilon_{0}n_{b}\pi\mathcal{L}}\sum_{n,m}\int_{0}^{\infty}dk\, k\left|\mu_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\right|^{2}\left(f_{ek}^{n}+f_{hk}^{m}-1\right)\frac{\gamma}{\left(\omega_{n,m}(\mathbf{k})-\nu\right)^{2}+\gamma^{2}},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is the length of the 2D quantum system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Spontaneous Emission
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spontaneous emission within a semiconductor nanostructure can be obtained
 from the amplification 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 of the photon field, i.e.
 the complex part of the optical susceptibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 Using a phenomenological approach, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Absorption_FCT"

\end_inset

 can be divided into an emitting and an absorbing part, 
\begin_inset Formula $G=G_{e}-G_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{c\mathbf{k}}+n_{v\mathbf{k}}-1$
\end_inset

 is the inversion of the electron-hole population in the semiconductor,
 which can be rewritten to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
n_{c\mathbf{k}}+n_{v\mathbf{k}}-1=n_{c\mathbf{k}}n_{v\mathbf{k}}-\left(1-n_{c\mathbf{k}}\right)\left(1-n_{v\mathbf{k}}\right).\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first term on rhs denotes the probability of a photon emission, i.e.
 electron and hole is occupied, while the second term denotes the probability
 of a photon absorption.
 Therefore, by evaluating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Absorption_FCT"

\end_inset

 including only the emission probability term 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{e}\sim n_{c\mathbf{k}}n_{v\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

, the spontaneous emission probability per unit length is obtained.
 As the velocity of a photon in the semiconductor is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $c/n_{b}$
\end_inset

, the spontaneous emission probability per second is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{e}c/n_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Neglecting the existence of a cavity, the photon density of states (of
 photons with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

) is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
N(\hbar\omega)=\frac{n_{b}^{3}(\hbar\omega)^{2}}{\pi^{2}\hbar^{3}c^{3}}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and therefore the spontaneous emission (
\begin_inset Formula $s^{−1}m^{−3}eV^{−1}$
\end_inset

) per second per unit volume per unit energy is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
r_{sp}(\hbar\omega)=\frac{n_{b}^{3}(\hbar\omega)^{2}}{\pi^{2}\hbar^{3}c^{2}}G_{e}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where as the spontaneous emission intensity (
\begin_inset Formula $s^{−1}m^{−3}$
\end_inset

) is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
I_{sp}\left(\hbar\omega\right)=\hbar\omega r_{sp}\left(\hbar\omega\right).\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the result can be related to the Kubo-Martin-Schwinger (KMS) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Martin1959a"

\end_inset

 relation.
 The relation between emission and inversion gives
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{f_{c\mathbf{k}}f_{v\mathbf{k}}}{f_{c\mathbf{k}}+f_{v\mathbf{k}}-1}=\frac{1}{1-\exp\left(\left(E_{c}(\mathbf{k})-E_{v}(\mathbf{k})-\left(E_{Fc}-E_{Fv}\right)\right)/k_{B}T\right)}.\label{eq:Inversion_Emmision_Relation}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Due to the Lorentzian in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Absorption_FCT"

\end_inset

, the transition energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{c}(\mathbf{k})-E_{v}(\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

 is close to the photon energy.
 Consequently, it may be replaced with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

 on the r.h.s of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Inversion_Emmision_Relation"

\end_inset

, which allows to pull the factor 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Inversion_Emmision_Relation"

\end_inset

 out of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-sum in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Absorption_FCT"

\end_inset

, leading to the KMS relation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
r_{sp}(\hbar\omega)=\frac{n_{b}^{2}(\hbar\omega)^{2}}{\pi^{2}\hbar^{3}c^{2}}\frac{1}{1-\exp\left(\left(\hbar\omega-\left(E_{Fc}-E_{Fv}\right)\right)/k_{B}T\right)}G(\hbar\omega)\label{eq:Sp_Emission_Definition}\end{equation}

\end_inset

between gain and spontaneous emission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another aspect to consider is the dependence of the dipole matrix element
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{cv,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 on the polarization of the light field.
 Therefore, the average of all possible transitions is usually taken for
 the spontaneous emission
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mu_{cv,\mathbf{k}}^{sp}=\frac{1}{3}\sum_{i=x,y,z}\mu_{cv,\mathbf{k}}^{i}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The spontaneous emission rate per unit volume (
\begin_inset Formula $s^{−1}m^{−3}$
\end_inset

) is given by integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{sp}(\hbar\omega)$
\end_inset

 over the energy
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
R_{sp}=\int_{0}^{\infty}r_{sp}(\hbar\omega)d\hbar\omega=Bnp\end{equation}

\end_inset

which defines another figure of merit, the spontaneous emission 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 coefficient (
\begin_inset Formula $m^{3}s^{−1}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is an obvious pathological feature when such a relation is used to
 obtain the spontaneous emission: if the electric field is zero, then no
 spontaneous emission would exist.
 The root of this misbehavior is due to the fact that the quantization of
 the electro-magnetic field is not included.
 Including this, spontaneous emission would occur - spontaneously.
 Nevertheless, the spontaneous emission of a two level system treated using
 quantized electro-magnetic fields does not differ from dipole radiation,
 therefore the error of the classical treatment may be small enough for
 the present purpose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Dipole-Matrix-Element"

\end_inset

Dipole Matrix Element
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evaluation of the interband dipole matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}_{mn,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 between the solutions of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 band structure calculation is not straight-forward.
 In the general case, the envelope functions are given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\varphi_{m\mathbf{k}}=\sum_{i}F_{m,i\mathbf{k}}u_{i0},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i0}$
\end_inset

 are again zone-center Bloch functions.
 Using this expansion, the dipole matrix element between two states is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\mu}_{n'n,\mathbf{k}}=\mathcal{A}\int_{\mathcal{L}}dz\sum_{i,j}u_{i0}^{*}F_{m,i\mathbf{k}}^{*}\mathbf{d}u_{j0}F_{n,j\mathbf{k}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The question to answer is to whether the dipole operator is acting on the
 lattice periodic part 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j0}$
\end_inset

 or on the envelope part 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The issue has been addressed by Burt and others 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Burt1995,Burt1993"

\end_inset

, concluding that the expression is dominated by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\mu}_{n'n,\mathbf{k}}\approx\frac{\mathcal{A}}{V_{c}}\sum_{i,j}\left\langle u_{i0}\mid u_{j0}\right\rangle _{V_{c}}\int_{\mathcal{L}}dzF_{m,i\mathbf{k}}^{*}\mathbf{d}F_{n,j\mathbf{k}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

But, within a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 calculation involving only single-band models for both, conduction and
 valence band, the last expression evaluates due to the orthogonality of
 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{c0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{v0}$
\end_inset

 to zero
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This fact also applies to 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times6$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 valence band models.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, no transition between conduction and valence subbands in such
 models would exist.
 The reason lies in the single-band approximation.
 While the wavefunction of e.g.
 conduction subbands is dominated by the envelope modulating 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{c0}$
\end_inset

, the interband dipole moment is dominated by the admixture of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{v0}$
\end_inset

 into the conduction subbands and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{c0}$
\end_inset

 into the valence subbands.
 Working within the 
\begin_inset Formula $8\times8$
\end_inset

 model would therefore resolve the problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simpler solution, allowing to use non-
\begin_inset Formula $8\times8$
\end_inset

 models without the pathological feature of vanishing transition probabilities,
 is to use the momentum- instead of the dipole matrix element.
 The relation can be derived using the Heisenberg equation of motion for
 the position operator 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{r}=\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[H,\mathbf{r}\right].\end{equation}

\end_inset

Assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 are eigenfunctions of the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 with corresponding eigenenergies 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{m}$
\end_inset

, replacing the derivative of the position operator by the momentum operator
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H\left|m\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{m}\left|m\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 , one obtains
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\langle n\mid\mathbf{p}\mid m\right\rangle =\frac{im}{\hbar}\left(E_{n}-E_{m}\right)\left\langle n\mid\mathbf{r}\mid m\right\rangle .\end{equation}

\end_inset

The electron dipole operator (electrons are negatively charged) is related
 to the position operator by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{d}=e\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 leading to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\langle n\mid\mathbf{d}\mid m\right\rangle =e\frac{\hbar}{im}\frac{\left\langle n\mid\mathbf{p}\mid m\right\rangle }{\left(E_{n}-E_{m}\right)}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

Within direct transitions, the energy difference 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}-E_{m}$
\end_inset

 can be replaced by the photon energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

, leading to the simple expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}_{mn,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the momentum matrix element
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\mu}_{mn,\mathbf{k}}=\frac{e}{im\omega}\mathbf{p}_{mn,\mathbf{k}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the approximation of slowly varying envelopes, the derivatives of the
 envelopes are small and the momentum matrix element is dominated by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{p}_{mn,\mathbf{k}}\approx\frac{\mathcal{A}}{V_{c}}\sum_{i,j}\left\langle u_{i0}\mid\mathbf{p}\mid u_{j0}\right\rangle _{V_{c}}\int_{\mathcal{L}}dzF_{m,i\mathbf{k}}^{*}F_{n,j\mathbf{k}}.\label{eq:Momentum_Matrix_Element_Approx}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The momentum matrix elements are related via 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Matrix_Elements_Relation"

\end_inset

 to band structure parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, defined e.g.
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Valence_Band_Edge_Energy"

\end_inset

.
 This approximation is commonly applied and is also used in the remainder
 of the thesis.
\end_layout

